{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470938"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"281"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471238"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:46:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:46:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"281"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/281"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.06,0.03,0.68,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101211"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/281"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83650"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"303"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34852"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44023"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101211"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of rhinorrhoea and dry cough. Today he has developed wheeze and increased work of breathing. His feeding has decreased. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has not had similar symptoms previously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed and lethargic. His pulse rate is 150/min, respiratory rate 40/min, SpO2 89% on room air (improving to 99% with supplemental oxygen), and temperature 37.5\u00b0C. He has nasal flaring, subcostal recession, tracheal tug, and an audible wheeze. A nasopharyngeal swab performed yesterday was negative for COVID-19.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Sputum microscopy and culture","Complete blood examination","None required","Urine microscopy and culture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with the classic features of viral bronchiolitis: coryzal symptoms progressing to respiratory distress with wheeze and increased work of breathing. The diagnosis is clinical, and \u003Cstrong\u003Enone\u003C/strong\u003E of the listed investigations are required in a previously well infant with typical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as routine imaging may lead to unnecessary antibiotic use without improving outcomes. Chest X-ray should be reserved for cases where there is diagnostic uncertainty or severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in bronchiolitis as it is a viral illness. Additionally, obtaining sputum samples from infants is impractical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete blood examination\u003C/strong\u003E does not assist in diagnosis or management of bronchiolitis and should not be performed routinely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. While young infants with fever may require urine testing to exclude urinary tract infection, this child\u0027s presentation is clearly explained by bronchiolitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBronchiolitis is the most common lower respiratory tract infection in infants under 12 months. The illness is self-limiting, typically lasting 7-10 days, with symptoms peaking around day 3-5. Management focuses on supportive care including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E Oxygen supplementation if required (target\u00a0SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E is \u226590%, unless there is specific underlying disease with specific targets) typically delivered via nasal prongs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaintaining hydration through regular feeds or NGT hydration if required\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonitoring of respiratory status (work of breathing)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Viral bronchiolitis is a clinical diagnosis requiring no routine investigations in previously well infants.","Bronchiolitis typically presents with coryzal symptoms followed by increased work of breathing and feeding difficulties.","The mainstay of management for bronchiolitis is supportive care with supplemental oxygen to maintain saturations \u226590%."],"references":["Paediatric Research in Emergency Departments International Collaborative. Australasian Bronchiolitis Guideline [online]. 2016. Available at: www.predict.org.au","Friedman JN, Rieder MJ, Walton JM; Canadian Paediatric Society, Acute Care Committee, Drug Therapy and Hazardous Substances Committee. Bronchiolitis: Recommendations for diagnosis, monitoring and management of children one to 24 months of age. Paediatr Child Health. 2014 Nov;19(9):485-98. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4235450/","Bronchiolitis. The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Nov 2023. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Bronchiolitis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83650"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"281"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83650"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T07:30:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T07:31:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"281"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101211"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.eme